T1  - Are IMF rescue packages effective? A synthetic control analysis of macroeconomic crises
AU  - Kuruc, Kevin
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 127
SP  - 38
EP  - 53
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/04/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jmoneco.2022.02.002
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304393222000198
KW  - IMF
KW  - Financial crises
KW  - Synthetic controls
KW  - Business cycle policy
AB  - Whether, and to what degree, IMF lending succeeds in stabilizing economies remains an open question. Here, a synthetic control analysis of macroeconomic crises with IMF intervention is performed—leveraging the existence of similar crises without intervention—that finds positive recovery effects. In the first five years following a crisis, output differences are, on average, nearly two percent of GDP per year. Consistent with a liquidity channel, effects are hump-shaped and fade in the medium run. An analysis of historical IMF forecasts provides evidence against selection as a spurious driver of this result, suggesting that these positive estimates are indeed causal.
